Before Cam broke his right arm, he was able to type at a speed of 9 words per minute. Therefore, in 5 minutes, he would be able to type:

\[ 9 \text{ words/minute} \times 5 \text{ minutes} = 45 \text{ words} \]

After breaking his right arm and having to use his left hand, Cam's typing speed decreased to 6 words per minute. Therefore, in the same period of 5 minutes, he would be able to type:

\[ 6 \text{ words/minute} \times 5 \text{ minutes} = 30 \text{ words} \]

To find the difference between the number of words Cam could type before and after breaking his arm in a span of 5 minutes, we subtract the lower amount from the higher:

\[ 45 \text{ words} - 30 \text{ words} = 15 \text{ words} \]

Therefore, the difference is \( \boxed{15} \) words.
